{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.13,0.05,0.06,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78028"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44768"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78028"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless swelling in his neck. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer daily. He works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 122/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His BMI is 26 kg/m2. There is a firm, non-tender fullness in his left supraclavicular fossa. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hodgkin\u0027s disease","Branchial cyst","Goitre","Carcinoma of the tongue","Carcinoma of the stomach"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with left supraclavicular lymphadenopathy (Troisier\u0027s sign), which is highly suggestive of underlying malignancy. The CT scan shows a mass of enlarged nodes in the left supraclavicular fossa. The lymphatic drainage from the stomach travels up through the thoracic duct and can result in left supraclavicular node involvement. This patient\u0027s age, male gender, and smoking history are risk factors for gastric cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E commonly presents with metastatic disease, and left supraclavicular lymphadenopathy may be the first sign. The absence of early symptoms is typical, as gastric cancer often remains clinically silent until advanced stages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHodgkin\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy, but it usually begins in the cervical or axillary nodes and follows a predictable pattern of spread. Isolated supraclavicular involvement would be unusual, and patients often have B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in younger patients (20-30 years) and is usually located in the lateral neck, anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. It would be unusual for it to present for the first time in a 56-year-old man.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoitre\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the thyroid gland in the anterior neck and moves with swallowing. It would not cause isolated supraclavicular lymphadenopathy as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the tongue\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with oral symptoms and would cause ipsilateral cervical lymphadenopathy in levels I-III, rather than in the supraclavicular fossa (level V).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Left supraclavicular lymphadenopathy (Troisier\u0027s sign) strongly suggests underlying gastric cancer due to lymphatic drainage patterns.","Painless cervical lymphadenopathy requires thorough investigation as it may represent metastatic disease.","Risk factors for gastric cancer include smoking, male gender, and age over 50 years."],"references":["Adler C, Lubner MG, Menias CO, et al. What\u2019s in\u00a0a\u00a0node? The clinical and\u00a0radiologic significance of\u00a0Virchow\u2019s node. Abdo Radiol 2022; 47:2244-53."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"352"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/352"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c989397-bce0-4968-a7a6-4247f1b8fcd4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c989397-bce0-4968-a7a6-4247f1b8fcd4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":517,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T09:40:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T09:41:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"